metropoles and simultaneously impoverished their peripheries. To account for this atrocity, Scott examines moral and reparatory modes of history and criticism, probing different conceptions of evil. He reflects on the paradoxes of seeking redress for the specific moral evil of slavery, criticizing the limitations of liberal rights-based arguments for reparations that pursue reconciliation with the past. Instead, this book argues, in making the urgent demand for reparations, we must acknowledge the fundamental irreparability of a wrong of such magnitude.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEnslaved personszAmericaxHistory. 0aEnslaved personszCaribbean AreaxHistory. 0aReparations for historical injusticeszAmerica. 0aReparations for historical injusticeszCaribbean Area. 0aSlaveryxMoral and ethical aspectszAmerica. 0aSlaveryxMoral and ethical aspectszCaribbean Area. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh  aforgiveness.  ahistoriography.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/scot2130440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231559690423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231559690/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles